How the Model Works

Overview

The Prediction Method

The model predicts player points using a simple but effective approach:

Predicted Points = 0.5  (Last 5 Game Avg) + 0.5  (Last 10 Game Avg)

Why This Works

  1. Rolling averages smooth out noise - One bad or great game doesnt throw off predictions
  2. Recent form matters - The 5-game average captures if a player is hot or cold
  3. Baseline matters too - The 10-game average captures their typical output
  4. Simplicity wins - Complex models overfit; simple models generalize

The Betting Decision

Edge = Sportsbook Line - Our Prediction

If Edge >= 3 points AND odds >= -115 AND bet is UNDER:
     BET (confidence based on edge size)
Else:
     PASS

Why UNDERS Only?

The Explanation

Why UNDERS work: - When a player has a high line, it often means theyve been scoring well recently - The models rolling average predicts regression - theyll likely score closer to their norm - Betting UNDER captures this regression

Why OVERS fail: - When a player has a low line, betting over requires them to exceed expectations - The model isnt good at predicting when players will break out - Sportsbooks price overs more accurately

The Vig Problem

Why Most Betting Loses

Player prop odds are NOT -110 (the standard). They average -135 to -170.

Bet Type Average Odds % Worse than -110
Over -176 57%
Under -182 60%

What This Means

At -135 average odds, you need to win 57.4% just to break even.

The model wins 58-62% of bets, but thats barely above break-even for these odds.

Solution: Only bet when you find odds of -115 or better through line shopping.

Confidence Levels Explained

How We Define Confidence

Level Edge Odds Historical ROI Why
HIGH 4+ pts >= -115 +6.7% Large edge overcomes vig
MEDIUM 3-4 pts >= -115 +2.5% Moderate edge, still profitable
LOW 2-3 pts >= -115 ~0% Edge too small for vig
AVOID Any < -115 OR Over -7% to -12% Vig eats all profit

The Math Behind It

At -115 odds: - Break-even win rate: 53.5% - Model wins at edges: - 4+ pts: 51.4% (profitable because better odds) - 3+ pts: 50.8% (marginally profitable) - 2+ pts: 49.5% (break-even)

Key insight: We dont need to win more than 50% if were getting plus odds or low vig. Line shopping moves us from -135 average to -105/-115, dramatically changing the math.

What NOT To Do

  • Never bet OVERS - They lose 10%+ ROI historically
  • Never bet bad odds - Anything worse than -115 eats your profit
  • Never bet small edges - Under 3 points isnt worth the risk
  • Never bet everything - Be selective, not comprehensive

Methodology

The Elastic Net Model

The prediction model is an Elastic Net regression (a regularized linear model that combines L1 and L2 penalties). It was trained on player-game data from before January 2024, then tested out-of-sample on 2024-2025 data.

Model Features (12 predictors)

Feature Coefficient Description
career_avg_pts +0.465 Career scoring average (most important)
roll_pts_9 +0.214 9-game rolling average points
roll_mp_3 +0.092 3-game rolling average minutes
roll_pts_3 +0.084 3-game rolling average points
roll_usg_5 +0.078 5-game rolling usage percentage
roll_pts_5 +0.033 5-game rolling average points
roll_pts_7 +0.023 7-game rolling average points
roll_usg_3 +0.011 3-game rolling usage percentage
days_rest -0.010 Days since last game
roll_3pa_3 -0.020 3-game rolling 3-point attempts
roll_pts_sd_5 -0.021 5-game scoring variance (consistency)
(Intercept) -1.476 Baseline adjustment

Model MAE: 4.67 points (competitive with Vegas lines)

Why These Features Matter

  • Career average dominates (0.465): Players tend to regress toward their long-term mean
  • Longer rolling windows matter more (0.214 for 9-game vs 0.084 for 3-game): Recent hot/cold streaks are noise
  • Minutes predict points (0.092): More playing time = more scoring opportunities
  • Variance is penalized (-0.021): Inconsistent scorers are harder to predict

How the Backtest Works

The backtest simulates what would have happened if we followed different betting strategies from May 2023 through November 2025.

Step 1: Data Collection

  • Betting lines: 320,700 player point prop lines from The Odds API (7 major sportsbooks)
  • Player stats: 84,668 player-game records from Basketball Reference
  • Matched records: 56,507 games where we have both a prediction and betting lines

Step 2: Generate Predictions

For each player-game, the Elastic Net model predicts expected points using the features above. All features use lagged data (we only know what happened before the game).

Step 3: Calculate Edge

Edge = Model Prediction - Vegas Line
  • Positive edge: Model thinks player will score MORE than the line (bet OVER)
  • Negative edge: Model thinks player will score LESS than the line (bet UNDER)

Step 4: Apply Betting Rules

For each strategy, we filter bets by:

  1. Edge threshold: Only bet when |edge| >= X points (e.g., 3 points)
  2. Odds threshold: Only bet when odds >= Y (e.g., -115 or better)
  3. Bet type: Over, Under, or best available

Step 5: Calculate P&L

For each qualifying bet:

  • Win: Payout based on American odds (e.g., -115 pays $86.96 on $100 bet)
  • Loss: Lose $100 stake
  • Push: Line equals actual points, bet returned

Step 6: Aggregate Results

  • ROI = Total P&L / Total Amount Wagered
  • Win Rate = Wins / Total Bets

Why Unders Win

The backtest consistently shows UNDERS outperform OVERS. Why?

  1. Regression to the mean: Hot streaks dont last. If a player scored 35 points last game, theyre more likely to score closer to their average next game.

  2. Injury/rest effects: Players often sit out or play limited minutes, resulting in under their line.

  3. Line-setting bias: Sportsbooks may shade lines toward overs because casual bettors like betting on points being scored.

  4. Our model captures this: The large positive coefficient on career_avg_pts (0.465) pulls predictions toward long-term averages, naturally favoring unders after hot streaks.

Walk-Forward Validation

To ensure no look-ahead bias, we also ran a walk-forward backtest that retrains the model every week:

  1. Train on all data before Week N
  2. Predict Week N games
  3. Add Week N results to training data
  4. Repeat for Week N+1

This simulates real-world usage where youd retrain periodically with new data.

Results Comparison (UNDERS at -105 odds)

Edge Threshold Static Model ROI Walk-Forward ROI
3.0 points 15.6% 15.4%
2.5 points 13.8% 14.2%
4.0 points 14.4% 13.2%
2.0 points 11.4% 11.1%

Key Finding: Results are nearly identical, confirming:

  • The edge is real and persists over time
  • No look-ahead bias in the static model
  • Weekly retraining doesnt significantly change results
  • The strategy is robust to different validation approaches
